In the K-means algorithm, cluster centroids (μk) are updated at each iteration to minimize the sum of squared distances between data points and their assigned centroids. The formula used for this update is:
μk = (Σ xᵢI(zᵢ = k)) / (Σ I(zᵢ = k))
Here:
- xᵢ represents iᵗʰ data point in the dataset.
- zᵢ represents the cluster assignment for data point xᵢ, where zᵢ is an integer indicating the cluster index (k).
Suppose you have a dataset of 9 two-dimensional data points and are performing K-means clustering with K = 3 clusters. After the first iteration, clusters C₁, C₂, and C₃ have the following data points:
C₁: {(2, 2), (3, 3), (4, 4)}
C₂: {(6, 6), (7, 7),(8, 8)}
C₃: {(10, 10), (11, 11), (12, 12)}

Let X₁, X₂, ..., Xn be n i.i.d. samples with parameter θ, which follows one of the following PDFs:
For θ = -1, we have
f(x|θ) = { 5x⁴, if 0 < x < 1; 0, otherwise }
For θ = 1, we have
f(x|θ) = { 1, if 0 < x < 1; 0, otherwise }
